I saw Ken Burns speak at PBS a few years ago, and he said that one of the reason he&#039;s dedicated his life to making long movies is that he wants to fight against the war on our focus. &quot;Our focus is the most precious thing we have.&quot;
For me and for many people our age (if I may be so bold - I know you&#039;re almost a generation younger), this is the defining struggle of our adulthood. How can we give enough sustained attention to the things that are most rewarding?
(I really wish I could track down the translation of the words that are hung in the tournament room of the Nihon Kiin that&#039;s shown so many times in Hikaru no Go. I think they say something relevant...)
For me, I don&#039;t try to focus better in order to improve my go. I play go because the way it teaches me to focus is one of the most important things for my soul. When I approach an important game, I go through rituals that help me prepare for something deep and all-consuming. I make tea, or I make myself a place to sit. I close down other apps (if I&#039;m on the computer), then I place the computer where I can see it but where I have to rise in order to play a move. Then I try to imagine Shifu sitting over my shoulder, like Sai. And then I tell myself to smile. &quot;Onegaishimasu!&quot;
I don&#039;t do all of this every time, but when I do I find I get to a better place with my go. And it serves as a model for how to approach anything important in my life.
